The following passage describes a runtime weight precision swap mechanism for on-device large language model inference. Read it carefully and continue the explanation. The key insight is that during a precision swap, weights of individual layers are replaced atomically while decoding continues, and the choice of how many layers to swap per decode step controls the latency profile observed by the user. Specifically, swapping less leads to higher latency but lower memory usage due to reduced layer count; swapping more results in lower latency at a cost of increased memory usage.

The precise trade-off is determined by an algorithm that takes into account both model size and decoding requirements.
